<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1436,151,1039]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,800,824]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[323,614,800,824]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Sphaeropthalma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amphion">
<emphasis box="[323,614,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Sphaeropthalma amphion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were too rarely encountered to determine their habitat preference. Only one 
<taxonomicName box="[199,325,836,860]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Sphaeropthalma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amphion">
<emphasis box="[199,325,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">S. amphion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
male was collected in late October at a light trap. Ten 
<taxonomicName box="[943,1069,836,860]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Sphaeropthalma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amphion">
<emphasis box="[943,1069,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">S. amphion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males were found at the NTS in August at light traps and a mammal trap (
<bibRefCitation author="Ferguson" box="[644,820,871,895]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refString="Ferguson, W. E. (1967) Male Sphaeropthalmine mutillid wasps of the Nevada Test Site. Brigham Young University Science Bulletin, 8 (4), 1 - 26." type="journal article" year="1967">
Ferguson 
<number box="[760,820,871,895]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="1967.0">1967</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). This species is widespread throughout much of the western 
<collectingCountry box="[245,395,908,932]" name="United States of America" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">United States</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pitts" box="[409,592,908,932]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refString="Pitts, J. P., Parker, F. D. &amp; Pitts-Singer, T. L. (2004) A review of the Sphaeropthalma uro species-group (Hymenoptera: Mutillidae), with taxonomic changes. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 77, 223 - 234." type="journal article" year="2004">
Pitts 
<emphasis box="[468,524,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[531,592,908,932]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Host data and taxonomy for this species is presented in 
<bibRefCitation box="[1233,1431,908,932]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refString="Pitts, J. P., Parker, F. D. &amp; Pitts-Singer, T. L. (2004) A review of the Sphaeropthalma uro species-group (Hymenoptera: Mutillidae), with taxonomic changes. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 77, 223 - 234." type="journal article">
Pitts 
<emphasis box="[1290,1347,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[1361,1423,908,932]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="2004.0">2004</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. For this study we have designated a 
<typeStatus box="[558,660,943,967]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">lectotype</typeStatus>
from the available 
<typeStatus box="[879,981,944,968]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">syntypes</typeStatus>
. We selected the 
<typeStatus box="[1173,1276,943,967]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">lectotype</typeStatus>
from the only specimen available. The label data are as follows [Nev.] [
<typeStatus box="[820,878,981,1005]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Type</typeStatus>
no. 
<number box="[934,993,980,1004]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="4654.0">4654</number>
] [
<taxonomicName authority="Fox" authorityName="Fox" box="[1017,1219,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Sphaeropthalma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amphion">M. amphion Fox</taxonomicName>
]. The metasoma is broken off, but is still with pinned portion of the specimen.
</paragraph>
